<session_management_guide>
<title>SESSION MANAGEMENT VULNERABILITIES</title>

<critical>Session management flaws enable session hijacking, fixation, and unauthorized access. Focus on session fixation, session puzzling, concurrent session handling, token entropy, timeout issues, and cross-subdomain leakage. Weak session handling leads to account takeover without credentials.</critical>

<scope>
- Session fixation attacks
- Session puzzling and variable overwriting
- Concurrent session handling issues
- Session token entropy analysis
- Session timeout and expiration problems
- Cross-subdomain session leakage
- Session riding (CSRF variant)
- Session donation attacks
- Logout incomplete session invalidation
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Analyze session tokens: cookies, headers, storage location
2. Test fixation: set session before and after authentication
3. Test concurrent sessions: login multiple times simultaneously
4. Measure entropy: collect tokens, analyze randomness
5. Test expiration: idle timeout, absolute timeout, logout behavior
6. Test scope: subdomain isolation, path restrictions, secure flags
7. Test persistence: survive browser close, password change, account changes
8. Test inheritance: session data overwriting, variable confusion
</methodology>

<session_fixation>
<attack_pattern>
1. Attacker gets session ID from target site (unauthenticated)
2. Attacker sends session ID to victim (URL, cookie)
3. Victim authenticates with attacker's session ID
4. Attacker uses same session ID → now authenticated as victim

Example:
http://target.com/login?sessionid=ATTACKER_SESSION
Victim logs in, server doesn't regenerate session ID
Attacker uses ATTACKER_SESSION → hijacks victim account
</attack_pattern>

<test_methodology>
1. Request site, capture session cookie (PHPSESSID, JSESSIONID, etc)
2. Send session cookie to victim (or in URL parameter)
3. Victim authenticates
4. Use original session cookie
5. Check if now authenticated as victim

curl -c cookies.txt http://target.com/
SESS=$(grep session cookies.txt | awk '{print $7}')
# Send to victim: http://target.com/?sessionid=$SESS
# Victim logs in
curl -b "sessionid=$SESS" http://target.com/profile
# If shows victim data: vulnerable to fixation
</test_methodology>

<session_id_sources>
- Cookies: PHPSESSID, JSESSIONID, connect.sid
- URL parameters: sessionid=, sid=, token=
- POST body: hidden form fields
- HTTP headers: X-Session-Token, Authorization
- HTML5 storage: localStorage.sessionId
</session_id_sources>
</session_fixation>

<session_puzzling>
<variable_overloading>
- Application uses same session variable in different contexts
- Context 1: sets user.role = "temp" for unauthenticated
- Context 2: checks user.role for authorization
- Attacker manipulates flow to set privileged value

Example:
1. Visit /admin-panel → sets session.adminAccess = false
2. Visit /forgot-password?adminAccess=true → overwrites session var
3. Session.adminAccess now true
4. Access /admin-panel → authorized due to session variable
</variable_overloading>

<session_injection>
- Inject session variables via query params, forms
- ?is_admin=true, ?role=admin, ?user_type=administrator
- Backend assigns to session without validation

Test:
GET /any-page?session[role]=admin
POST /update-profile
{
  "session": {"is_admin": true}
}
</session_injection>
</session_puzzling>

<concurrent_sessions>
<multiple_active_sessions>
- User can be logged in from multiple devices/browsers
- No limit on concurrent sessions
- Compromised session remains active

Impact:
- Attacker steals session, creates new one
- Victim logs in again, both sessions valid
- Attacker maintains access indefinitely
</multiple_active_sessions>

<session_race_conditions>
- Parallel requests with same session
- Session data corruption due to concurrent writes
- Race in session update logic

Example:
Thread 1: session.balance = 100; session.balance -= 50;
Thread 2: session.balance = 100; session.balance -= 30;
Final: session.balance = 70 (expected: 20)
</session_race_conditions>
</concurrent_sessions>

<session_token_entropy>
<weak_randomness>
- Predictable session IDs enable hijacking
- Sources of weak entropy:
  - MD5(sequential ID)
  - Timestamp + user ID
  - Auto-incrementing integers
  - Math.random() (not crypto-secure)

Analysis method:
1. Collect 20+ session IDs
2. Look for patterns: sequential, time-based, low entropy
3. Try to predict next session ID
4. Test prediction by creating new session and comparing
</weak_randomness>

<entropy_calculation>
- Minimum: 128 bits of entropy (OWASP recommendation)
- Session ID length vs character set:
  - 32 hex chars: 128 bits ✓
  - 16 hex chars: 64 bits ✗ (brute-forceable)
  - 10 digits: 33 bits ✗ (weak)

Check:
sessionid="0123456789abcdef" (16 hex = 64 bits, insufficient)
sessionid="a7f3e9c2b8d4f1a6c9e7b3d8f2a5c1e9b4d7f3a8" (40 hex = 160 bits ✓)
</entropy_calculation>
</session_token_entropy>

<session_timeout_issues>
<no_idle_timeout>
- Session never expires due to inactivity
- Compromised session valid indefinitely
- Attacker accesses weeks/months later

Test:
1. Login, capture session cookie
2. Wait 24-72 hours without activity
3. Use session cookie
4. If still valid: no idle timeout
</no_idle_timeout>

<no_absolute_timeout>
- Session valid forever if kept active
- Even with idle timeout, can be refreshed indefinitely

Test:
1. Login
2. Make request every 30 minutes for 30 days
3. If session remains valid: no absolute timeout
</no_absolute_timeout>

<remember_me_vulnerabilities>
- "Remember me" token never expires
- Token not rotated after password change
- Persistent token reused across accounts

Test:
1. Login with "Remember me" checked
2. Capture persistent cookie
3. Clear other sessions, logout
4. Use persistent cookie after days/weeks
5. Change password, test if token still valid
</remember_me_vulnerabilities>
</session_timeout_issues>

<cross_subdomain_leakage>
<cookie_scope_issues>
- Cookie set for entire domain: .example.com
- Accessible from all subdomains
- Attacker controls subdomain (via injection, takeover)
- Steals cookies from main domain

Test:
1. Check cookie domain attribute
2. If Domain=.example.com: accessible to all subdomains
3. If attacker controls any.example.com: can read main cookies
4. Subdomain takeover → session hijacking
</cookie_scope_issues>

<secure_flag_missing>
- Secure flag not set on cookies
- Cookie sent over HTTP as well as HTTPS
- MITM can intercept over HTTP

Test:
1. Capture cookie: PHPSESSID=abc123; Secure?
2. If no Secure flag: vulnerable
3. Make HTTP request: http://target.com/ (not https)
4. Cookie sent in plaintext
</secure_flag_missing>

<httponly_missing>
- HttpOnly flag not set
- JavaScript can access: document.cookie
- XSS can steal session tokens

Test:
console.log(document.cookie);
// If session cookie visible: HttpOnly missing
</httponly_missing>
</cross_subdomain_leakage>

<logout_issues>
<incomplete_invalidation>
- Logout doesn't destroy session on server
- Session cookie remains valid after logout
- Attacker with old session can still access

Test:
1. Login, capture session cookie
2. Logout via UI
3. Use old session cookie
4. If still authenticated: incomplete invalidation
</incomplete_invalidation>

<client_side_logout>
- Logout only clears cookie client-side
- Server session remains active
- Restoring cookie restores session

Test:
1. Login, copy session cookie
2. Logout (clears cookie)
3. Re-inject session cookie
4. Access protected page
5. If authenticated: server didn't invalidate
</client_side_logout>

<csrf_logout>
- Logout endpoint vulnerable to CSRF
- Attacker forces victim logout
- DoS attack vector
</csrf_logout>
</logout_issues>

<session_donation>
<attack_scenario>
- Attacker creates account
- Attacker triggers action with their session
- Victim continues with attacker's session
- Victim's actions attributed to attacker's account

Example OAuth flow:
1. Attacker starts OAuth, gets code
2. Attacker sends code/state to victim
3. Victim completes OAuth with attacker's session
4. Victim's account linked to attacker's OAuth
</attack_scenario>
</session_donation>

<validation>
1. Session fixation: set session before auth, verify not regenerated after
2. Concurrent sessions: login twice, verify both sessions work
3. Entropy: collect 10+ tokens, analyze randomness, calculate bits
4. Timeout: test idle and absolute timeout durations
5. Scope: verify Secure, HttpOnly, Domain, Path attributes
6. Logout: verify server-side invalidation
7. Impact: demonstrate session hijacking leading to account access
</validation>

<false_positives>
- High-entropy tokens regenerated after authentication
- Proper idle (30 min) and absolute (8-24 hr) timeouts
- Secure, HttpOnly flags set correctly
- Server-side session invalidation on logout
- Concurrent session limits enforced
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Session hijacking (account takeover without credentials)
- Persistent unauthorized access (weak timeout)
- Cross-subdomain session theft
- Session fixation (attacker-controlled authentication)
- Privilege escalation (session puzzling)
- Account linking attacks (session donation)
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always check session regeneration after authentication—most critical test
2. Capture session cookies with browser DevTools Application tab
3. Use Burp Suite Session Handling to maintain session across tests
4. Test timeout with real wait times—automated tools may not catch
5. Check all cookie flags: Secure, HttpOnly, SameSite, Domain, Path
6. Test logout from multiple devices—verify all sessions invalidated
7. Session IDs in URLs are immediately suspicious—check for fixation
8. Calculate entropy: bits = length × log2(charset_size)
9. Test remember-me separately—often weaker than main session
10. Monitor Set-Cookie headers—verify session ID changes after login
11. Test password change—session should be invalidated/regenerated
12. Check for session in localStorage—less secure than HttpOnly cookies
</pro_tips>

<remember>Secure session management requires: high-entropy tokens, regeneration after authentication, server-side storage and invalidation, proper timeouts, Secure/HttpOnly/SameSite flags, and single-point-of-failure prevention via concurrent session limits. Any weakness enables account takeover.</remember>
</session_management_guide>
